comment_text:
What is the true motive of dog lovers?

Should dogs be allowed to live and roam the streets as freely as humans? This is the key question of this issue. First of all, in Western countries there are no street dogs. A dog only ends up on the street if it strays away from its owner. That’s why they are called “stray dogs” and not “street dogs.”

But in india, there are dogs that are born and raised on the streets itself. No civilized society in the world allows such a shameful practice. In America, if people see a dog alone on the street without an guardian, people will consider it a big danger. People will immediately call the police. In Britain, you will hardly see dogs roaming the streets. The Netherlands is a country that has 100% eradicated stray dogs. In Singapore, if you feed a dog in a public place, you will face a heavy fine. Only humans have the right to walk freely on the streets. In most developed countries, animals are not allowed to roam freely in public spaces. 

According to the World Health Organization, 20,000 people die annually from rabies caused by stray dog bites in India, as reported in 2024. (Please note carefully: this is not the number of people bitten by stray dogs, but the number of people who have died due to stray dog bites. In that case, the number of people affected by stray dog bites could be a hundred times higher than this.) But the indian government, as usual, does not accept this statistic. Instead, it vastly underestimates the number of deaths due to stray dogs bites. When the COVID-19 crisis was at its peak, thousands of people in India died every day due to a shortage of oxygen cylinders. This was broadcast live by all international media outlets. Yet, the Indian government declared in parliament that not even a single person died due to an oxygen cylinder shortage. This incident alone is proof of how reliable the indian government's statistics are. 

For the sake of stray dogs, dog lovers spent 2 crore rupees as lawyer’s fees, hired four lawyers, and even managed to get the Supreme Court’s verdict overturned. Who did this? And why spend so much money? Every year in India, because of diseases spread by stray dogs, along with the costs of sterilization programs and other related expenses, a business worth 36,000 crore rupees(4 Billion USD) takes place. Animal activist Veterinarian Dr. Muralidharan stated this in an interview( Veterinarian Dr. Muralidharan is already litigating cases in the Supreme Court on animal welfare issues). For pharmaceutical companies to keep their business running, stray dogs must continue to exist in street. That is why so many crores of rupees were spent to “save” these stray dogs. In other words, for them to make money, the children of middle-class families have to die. So where is the compassion in this? Yet, in front of the media, they act like tender-hearted saints full of mercy, like Lord Jesus.

Dog lovers, please think with at least some conscience. In any of these developed countries—China, Japan, South Korea, Singapore, Malaysia, the Arab countries, the European countries, America, Canada, Australia—has even one country allowed stray dogs to live and roam freely on the streets? You eat goat, fish, and chicken quite happily.  Aren’t they voiceless creatures too? Don’t you understand even now that pharmaceutical companies have brainwashed you through Blue Cross? People who are born into wealthy families and simply live off their father’s or husband’s property while calling themselves “animal lovers” can never understand the struggles of an middle class citizen. Their children play safely inside compound walls. These “animal lovers” don’t walk the streets themselves. They don’t go out at midnight after finishing night-shift jobs. If they need to go anywhere, they travel safely in cars. It is because of their arrogance rooted in money (and caste) that such “animal lovers” talk the way they do. From what they say, one thing is clear:

Animal Lovers = Human Haters

comment_text:
​I am fundamentally opposed to the killing of any animal. However, the reality of living with domestic dogs, or encountering stray animals, presents unavoidable challenges.
​Even well-cared-for household dogs can pose a risk; if one is not sufficiently vigilant, bites can occur. This is compounded by the fact that all dog breeds possess a naturally aggressive potential, regardless of which type you choose.
​My primary concern is for human well-being. While I acknowledge that humans are often flawed, in the debate between animal welfare and human safety, I believe we must address the issue of stray animals in our communities. Animals that are genuinely harmless and move freely are typically ignored, but those that pose a threat cannot be.
​Having spent time observing both dedicated pet owners and interactions with stray dogs, my conclusion remains firm: an animal, at the end of the day, is still an animal—and must be viewed through that lens of unpredictable instinct.

video_title: Stray Dog Verdict: Supreme Court to Announce Order in Stray Dogs Case on Nov 7 | NewsX
comment_text:
This order may wear the mask of “public safety,” but it reeks of a quick-fix mentality. Like… how do they expect already crammed shelters to magically hold thousands of dogs overnight? It’s like telling people to “remove poverty” without building jobs first.
Delhi and most Indian cities don’t have enough shelters, vets, vaccines, or trained handlers to pull this off humanely. What’ll happen instead? Dogs will be rounded up, transported like cargo, and many will die of stress or neglect in makeshift “shelters.” It’s not governance it’s optics.

Public safety and compassion can coexist, but it takes planning. Proper sterilisation drives, feeding zones, and educating people on coexistence are the sustainable routes. But our system loves headline solutions, not groundwork. These dogs didn’t invade our cities we erased their spaces, starved them, hit them with bikes, and then called them “menace.”
And now we dare to pass “orders” like we’re gods, deciding who gets to breathe free?

video_title: Stray Dog Verdict: Supreme Court to Announce Order in Stray Dogs Case on Nov 7 | NewsX
comment_text: If the Supreme Court truly wishes to keep stray dogs off public spaces, then let the same principle apply across all sectors — remove our native breeds from police dog squads, stop using animals for entertainment, tourism, and religious exhibitions, and end the daily butchering of cows, buffaloes, and other animals. India exports tonnes of fresh meat abroad each day — isn’t that also animal cruelty? Selective compassion isn’t justice; true empathy means protecting all animals, not just the ones we find inconvenient.

video_title: Stray Dog Verdict: Supreme Court to Announce Order in Stray Dogs Case on Nov 7 | NewsX
comment_text:
I see so many people thanking the Supreme Court today, and I just want to ask one simple question — when will you all stop hiding the failures of the government and the judiciary when it comes to real issues like rape, corruption, hooliganism, air pollution, murders, and road accidents? The list goes on, and yet, there’s silence. Why don’t we demand accountability from those in power - the government, the Supreme Court, the High Courts, Or the government authorities for these burning issues that destroy lives every single day? Why is all this anger suddenly directed toward stray dogs, who can neither speak nor have the power to stand up for themselves? Let’s be honest, if you truly want to stay safe from stray dogs, you can easily do so by following some basic civic guidelines. We, humans, are the most evolved species on this planet. We have choices, intelligence, and empathy. But sadly, we choose to direct our frustrations toward the voiceless, instead of questioning the system that’s responsible for our suffering. The truth is, the hatred many of you carry isn’t really for these innocent animals, it’s for the daily chaos, the injustice, and the inefficiency that we face because of corruption, poor infrastructure, and lack of civic sense. But since you can’t fight those bigger battles, you choose an easier one that too with those who can’t fight back. 
And before you reply to this comment, let me just say this — I’m a vegetarian. I’ve been taught compassion towards every living being on this earth. I’ve been taught that true humanity lies in coexistence and empathy. You might win a few arguments here in this comment section, but remember, when you meet your Creator, you’ll have to answer for the cruelty you showed to the most defenseless of His creations. Har Har Mahadev, Jai Pashupatinath. 🙏

comment_text:
What India Can do regarding street furkids:
Goal
Reduce street-dog population and rabies incidence, improve public safety and dog welfare, by implementing a humane, scalable program combining mass sterilisation & vaccination, waste management, law & enforcement, and community engagement — measurable progress within 5 years and robust control in 10–15 years.
Phase 0 — Immediate / Quick wins (0–12 months)
Purpose: stop new deterioration, build capacity, communicate. Actions:
National task force (central + state veterinary/public health + NGOs) set up to coordinate policy and funding.
Mass public awareness campaign on: don’t abandon pets, responsible feeding, rabies prevention, report dog-bite cases.
Emergency rabies response: ensure PEP (post-exposure prophylaxis) availability at district hospitals; fast-track training for health workers on bite management.
Pilot high-impact ABC (Animal Birth Control) zones in 10–20 cities with highest bite/rabies incidence to demonstrate model & collect data.
Garbage cleanup blitzes in pilot zones to show rapid results when food sources are removed.
KPIs (12 months): task force formed; pilots launched; PEP stockouts eliminated in pilot districts; public campaign reach metric (e.g., x million impressions).
Phase 1 — Scale sterilisation + vaccination (1–4 years)
Purpose: reduce birth rates and rabies reservoir; show measurable decline in bite/rabies. Actions:
Scale up ABC program: mobile sterilisation teams, fixed clinics, night-surgery schedules, trained para-vets. Prioritise high-density urban wards and hotspots identified in pilots.
Capture–Sterilize–Vaccinate–Release (CSVR) standard operating procedure (SOP) across states — release only after recovery.
Data system: unique ID tagging (collar + photo + GIS location) and central database to track sterilised/vaccinated dogs and coverage rates.
Finance model: central matching grants to states + municipal budgets + NGO partnerships + CSR funding to cover surgeries, vaccines, meds, logistics.
Training & certification: accredit surgeons/teams, quality standards, animal welfare auditing.
Community dog-feeding zones: designate controlled feeding spots (away from traffic/markets) while sterilisation occurs.
KPIs (by year 4): 70%+ vaccination coverage in target zones; sterilisation rate high enough to reduce effective reproductive rate (target varies, but aim for sterilising majority of fertile females in hotspots); measurable drop in dog-bite incidence in pilot zones.
Phase 2 — Waste & habitat control + policy reforms (3–8 years)
Purpose: remove food sources & institutionalize prevention. Actions:
Modern municipal solid-waste management: sealed bins, covered transfer points, daily collection in dense urban wards; ban open garbage dumping near residential/market areas.
Regulation: mandatory pet registration + microchipping, mandatory sterilisation for adopted/rescued animals (incentives/subsidies).
Strict anti-abandonment enforcement: fines + prosecution for deliberate abandonment.
Expand shelters & adoption networks: municipally funded temporary holding centers, NGO-run adoption drives, foster networks.
Integrate into urban planning: dog-proofing waste bins, market sanitation, community feeding infrastructure.
Education: school curriculum modules on animal welfare, rabies prevention and responsible pet ownership.
KPIs (by year 8): marked reduction in accessible food in urban hotspots; established registration coverage in major cities; sustained low rabies incidence; improved adoption rates from shelters.

In Support of the Supreme Court’s Decision on Relocation of Stray Dogs.

Public safety must always come first, and I wholeheartedly welcome and appreciate the recent decision of the Hon’ble Supreme Court of India to direct the relocation of stray dogs to shelters. This is not just a legal step—it is a humane and practical measure that balances compassion towards animals with the fundamental right of citizens to live without constant fear of attacks.

I speak from personal experience. Two years ago, I was bitten by a street dog, an incident that caused not only physical injury but also emotional distress. Just yesterday, I narrowly escaped another attack by a group of dogs in my locality. The fear and anxiety in that moment were overwhelming. My own younger brother was bitten by a stray dog about five years ago and I have witnessed the pain, medical treatment, and mental trauma such incidents cause.

The reality is that such attacks are not rare—they are happening daily in various parts of the country. Children, elderly citizens, and even able-bodied adults are vulnerable. The Supreme Court’s order to relocate stray dogs to shelters ensures two important things:

1. Safety of the public – by reducing the chances of sudden, unprovoked attacks on the streets.
2. Welfare of the animals – by placing them in designated shelters where they can receive care, food and medical attention.

This is a win-win situation. It prevents cruelty to animals while also protecting human lives. The decision acknowledges that uncontrolled street dog populations create a serious public health hazard, including the risk of rabies. It also shows that humane solutions are possible without resorting to inhumane practices.

I urge local authorities to implement this directive without delay. Public safety, especially for children, should never be compromised and this judgment is a significant step towards a safer, more compassionate society.

video_title: Supreme Court decision on Stray Dogs in Delhi
comment_text:
1. Public Safety is Non-Negotiable

Every year, thousands of people suffer from severe dog bites and rabies cases. Many parents have lost their children to such incidents. No society can ignore this reality. Protecting human life is the first duty of any government.

2. Selective Empathy is Not Real Empathy

There are people who post on Instagram or protest in support of stray dogs, but the same people eat chicken or mutton at dinner. If animals deserve empathy, then why only stray dogs? Why not all animals? This inconsistency shows that much of the support is emotional, not practical.

3. Adoption vs Protests

People come in large numbers to protest “in support of dogs,” but very few are ready to adopt even one dog. If you truly want them on the streets, then you should also be responsible for their care. Otherwise, emotional slogans do not solve the problem.

4. Shelters Protect BOTH Humans and Dogs

Moving stray dogs into shelters does not mean harming them. They will receive food, care, and medical attention. Meanwhile, citizens get cleaner, safer streets. This is a win-win solution for society.

5. Irrelevant Arguments Don’t Change the Issue

Some people say, “Remove tobacco companies first,” or “Stop spitting on streets.”
Yes, those are ALSO valid issues — but they are not related to the stray dog problem. Solving one issue doesn’t mean we can’t solve another. Let the government fix at least one problem at a time instead of stopping progress everywhere.

6. Equality Between Humans and Dogs is Not Logical

Nobody is killing dogs — they are being moved to shelters for safety. But expecting equal rights for animals and humans is unrealistic. The state has a responsibility to protect citizens first. Dogs deserve care, but not at the cost of risking human lives.

comment_text:
SC judgement has changed but The real question now is: will this judgment actually work in real life? Because India’s municipal systems often struggle with implementation, funding, and clear definitions — like what exactly counts as an ‘aggressive dog" .And one more critical thing: while we discuss stray dogs and their impact, it’s not okay to compare human crimes — like rape .
Every issue deserves its own serious conversation. Animals deserve humane treatment. Humans deserve dignity. We don’t solve problems by trashing either side.It’s true that women in India face serious safety issues — data from the National Crime Records Bureau (NCRB 2023) shows over 31,000 cases of rape were registered. That means society still has a long way to go in building trust and security for women.
But safety and respect shouldn’t become a battle of genders.
Crime is a human problem — and yes, there have also been reports where women were accused in sexual-assault or harassment cases against men. Though those numbers are smaller, they remind us that crime and morality don’t belong to one gender alone. The Supreme Court itself has acknowledged concerns about false accusations in some rape and dowry-harassment cases. It has repeatedly said that while protecting victims is essential, investigators and courts must also guard against misuse of the law and ensure fair trials for everyone

video_title: Supreme Court Orders Removal of Stray Dogs in Delhi | Activists and Pet lovers fume | Full Details
comment_text:
What India Can do regarding street furkids:
Goal
Reduce street-dog population and rabies incidence, improve public safety and dog welfare, by implementing a humane, scalable program combining mass sterilisation & vaccination, waste management, law & enforcement, and community engagement — measurable progress within 5 years and robust control in 10–15 years.
Phase 0 — Immediate / Quick wins (0–12 months)
Purpose: stop new deterioration, build capacity, communicate. Actions:
National task force (central + state veterinary/public health + NGOs) set up to coordinate policy and funding.
Mass public awareness campaign on: don’t abandon pets, responsible feeding, rabies prevention, report dog-bite cases.
Emergency rabies response: ensure PEP (post-exposure prophylaxis) availability at district hospitals; fast-track training for health workers on bite management.
Pilot high-impact ABC (Animal Birth Control) zones in 10–20 cities with highest bite/rabies incidence to demonstrate model & collect data.
Garbage cleanup blitzes in pilot zones to show rapid results when food sources are removed.
KPIs (12 months): task force formed; pilots launched; PEP stockouts eliminated in pilot districts; public campaign reach metric (e.g., x million impressions).
Phase 1 — Scale sterilisation + vaccination (1–4 years)
Purpose: reduce birth rates and rabies reservoir; show measurable decline in bite/rabies. Actions:
Scale up ABC program: mobile sterilisation teams, fixed clinics, night-surgery schedules, trained para-vets. Prioritise high-density urban wards and hotspots identified in pilots.
Capture–Sterilize–Vaccinate–Release (CSVR) standard operating procedure (SOP) across states — release only after recovery.
Data system: unique ID tagging (collar + photo + GIS location) and central database to track sterilised/vaccinated dogs and coverage rates.
Finance model: central matching grants to states + municipal budgets + NGO partnerships + CSR funding to cover surgeries, vaccines, meds, logistics.
Training & certification: accredit surgeons/teams, quality standards, animal welfare auditing.
Community dog-feeding zones: designate controlled feeding spots (away from traffic/markets) while sterilisation occurs.
KPIs (by year 4): 70%+ vaccination coverage in target zones; sterilisation rate high enough to reduce effective reproductive rate (target varies, but aim for sterilising majority of fertile females in hotspots); measurable drop in dog-bite incidence in pilot zones.
Phase 2 — Waste & habitat control + policy reforms (3–8 years)
Purpose: remove food sources & institutionalize prevention. Actions:
Modern municipal solid-waste management: sealed bins, covered transfer points, daily collection in dense urban wards; ban open garbage dumping near residential/market areas.
Regulation: mandatory pet registration + microchipping, mandatory sterilisation for adopted/rescued animals (incentives/subsidies).
Strict anti-abandonment enforcement: fines + prosecution for deliberate abandonment.
Expand shelters & adoption networks: municipally funded temporary holding centers, NGO-run adoption drives, foster networks.
Integrate into urban planning: dog-proofing waste bins, market sanitation, community feeding infrastructure.
Education: school curriculum modules on animal welfare, rabies prevention and responsible pet ownership.
KPIs (by year 8): marked reduction in accessible food in urban hotspots; established registration coverage in major cities; sustained low rabies incidence; improved adoption rates from shelters.

Both dog lovers and haters want the same thing → fewer dogs on the streets & fewer rabies/bite cases.

1️⃣ Impossible task – Crores of dogs can’t just be caught or killed. Even years of effort won’t succeed.
2️⃣ Vacuum effect – Remove dogs → new unvaccinated, often more aggressive ones take their place → more bites, more rabies.

4️⃣ Budget drain – Catching & sheltering lakhs of dogs = thousands of crores + massive space India doesn’t have. We have many other issues where this budget can be utilized.
5️⃣ Proven solution ignored – Sterilization + vaccination (ABC) works. It’s cost-effective, WHO-recommended, Indian law mandated. Govt has failed to scale it up.

👉 The truth: Only ABC reduces dogs on streets & protects people.

Before you come at me, I vaccinate and sterilize dogs every month from my own money. I adopted two rescues( indies) and most people like me who are fighting for strays are against breeds and breeding. 
Please don’t spread hate without knowing the full picture.

video_title: Supreme Court News | What The Supreme Court's Order On Delhi Stray Dogs Means
comment_text:
People keep calling themselves “animal lovers” when in reality, they’re just dog lovers. If they truly loved animals, they’d care for chickens, goats, fish, and even the so-called “ugly” creatures like cockroaches or snakes. But no, they happily eat mutton, chicken, and fish, while posting selfies with their imported breed dog. This isn’t love for animals, it’s selective affection for pets that make them feel good.

Street dogs are a serious public safety issue. Why should human children be taught to walk carefully, avoid eye contact, or carry sticks in their own streets? Streets are built for humans, not for territorial packs of animals. In nature, if an outsider enters a lion’s or dog’s territory, it’s attacked. Yet we’re told to “just be kind” while kids risk rabies, a disease that kills over 20,000 people in India every year.

And to those saying, “How can the government accommodate so many dogs?” — you are the reason this problem is out of control. You’re the ones stopping the municipality from catching dogs for years. You’re the ones feeding them on the streets, helping their numbers grow. You protect them from removal but then blame the government when the population explodes.

Also, stop confusing dog loyalty with “love for humans.” A dog is loyal to its pack, not to humanity. That’s just basic animal instinct. If you feed and protect it, you’re part of its pack. But to an unfamiliar child or passerby, the same “loyal” dog can turn aggressive because it sees them as an intruder in its territory. This is not betrayal — it’s exactly how wild animal packs behave. So no, a stray dog on the street is not automatically a friend just because it’s friendly to you.

Developed countries don’t allow free-roaming strays. They have shelters, strict breeding laws, and zero tolerance for animals attacking people. Here, activists feed strays in public, block municipal workers, and then act shocked when dog attacks rise. Feeding strays on the streets only increases their population and aggression. If you want to feed dogs, build a shelter and keep them there. Don’t make the whole community responsible for your choice.

Dog lives matter, yes. But human lives matter more. Protecting people and controlling stray populations is not cruelty, it’s common sense. If you oppose removing dangerous strays, you should be ready to take legal and financial responsibility if they harm someone. Until then, stop being a keyboard warrior and start being accountable.

video_title: Supreme Court News | What The Supreme Court's Order On Delhi Stray Dogs Means
comment_text:
The Supreme Court’s ruling on the removal of stray dogs from Delhi NCR must be respected, but it’s important to remember that such a decision, while made with the intent of human safety, also carries profound consequences for the animals involved. We must acknowledge the years of deliberation that went into this decision, but we must also think deeply about what comes next. The true challenge is not only removing the dogs but finding humane, sustainable solutions that respect all lives.
Can we manage stray dogs in a way that balances human safety and animal welfare? Modern technology and responsible animal care can provide us with options. We can implement GPS tracking, sterilization programs, and create well-managed, safe sanctuaries where stray dogs are cared for. This way, we not only address the issue of public safety but also respect the lives of these animals.

Some view dogs as a danger, while others see them as family members—these perspectives aren’t mutually exclusive. The truth lies in understanding that both viewpoints are rooted in concern, but solutions should come from compassion, not fear. To those who advocate for the complete removal of stray dogs, I ask: Do we, as humans, want to be known for abandoning those who need us most? We cannot abandon creatures simply because they seem inconvenient or unsafe in the short term. Instead, we must commit to long-term strategies that provide care and shelter.

Imagine this: When a person is left alone in their twilight years, when illness or frailty keeps them homebound, they may not have many friends left, but their dog will still be there. The dog’s love is unconditional. It’s a bond that lasts, offering comfort when no one else is around. Do we, as a society, want to be the ones who destroy that bond? Can we really call ourselves humane if we turn our backs on life, whether human or animal?

The solution isn’t in eradicating life, but in creating systems of care that work for both people and animals. We need to build better shelters, develop educational programs for communities, and provide support to those who are in a position to adopt and care for stray animals. Killing is never the answer. Protection, care, and compassion are the answers.

We have a choice: we can choose to act with love and responsibility, creating a future where both humans and animals can live safely and harmoniously. We must unite, not divide. The Supreme Court’s decision isn’t the final chapter—it's the beginning of a larger conversation that demands innovative, compassionate solutions. Together, we can find a way to balance human safety with the moral duty to protect and care for the animals that share our world.

Let’s stop acting out of fear and hatred and start acting with wisdom and compassion. We can do better. We must do better.

@nbdk

comment_text:
Why Stray Dog Removal Won’t Work

Both stray dog lovers and haters want the same thing → fewer dogs on the streets and fewer rabies/bite cases. Rabies is a problem for both humans and dogs. But removal is not the solution:
	1.	Impossible task – Catching or killing lakhs of dogs will take years and still won’t succeed.
	2.	Vacuum effect – New unvaccinated, more aggressive dogs will replace the removed ones → more bites, more rabies.
	3.	Global failures – Countries like China, Sri Lanka, and Romania tried culling but rabies/bites increased.
	4.	Huge cost – Thousands of crores and shelter space needed, which India doesn’t have.
	5.	Proven solution ignored – Sterilization + vaccination (ABC) is cost effective and proven worldwide. WHO recommends it, Indian law mandates it, but the government has failed to implement it all these years.

👉 ABC is the only way to truly reduce dogs on the streets and protect people.

video_title: Stray Dog Attack | Big Supreme Court Order On India's Stray Dog Menace
comment_text:
Loving Dogs Doesn't Mean Hating Humans

Being a dog lover doesn’t mean being blind to the challenges that come with stray animals. The government must take responsible and humane action to control the stray dog population. This includes establishing well-equipped animal shelters where stray dogs can live safely, reducing the risk of accidents and conflicts.

As a dog lover myself, I find such incidents deeply disturbing and unacceptable. Unfortunately, many dog owners and enthusiasts act irresponsibly — not understanding how to properly care for a dog or respect basic rules of pet ownership. It's essential to know how to manage dogs both at home and in public spaces.

Humans must acknowledge their responsibility toward animals. We should never harm or mistreat them unnecessarily. But at the same time, we must also recognize that not all dogs — whether stray or pet — are friendly or safe to approach.

Our environment has already been drastically altered by reckless development, which negatively impacts both humans and animals. Yet we often blame animals for behaving aggressively, without considering the conditions we’ve created.

Remember: dogs, like humans, have individual personalities. Not every dog wants affection — some simply need space. Showing excessive affection to an unfamiliar dog can provoke fear or aggression. It's always safer and more respectful to maintain a reasonable distance unless you're sure of the dog’s temperament.

Loving animals means understanding them, respecting boundaries, and advocating for responsible coexistence — not just for their safety, but for ours as well.

The Supreme Court ordered all stray dogs in Delhi to be sent to shelters. But these “dog prisons” aren’t the solution — expensive, stressful for the dogs, and they don’t stop rabies or aggression.

A smarter, humane alternative:

Vaccinate all dogs → stops rabies

Sterilize them → prevents overpopulation

Feed them properly → reduces fights and aggression


Goa’s example:

Rabies almost eliminated ✅

Fewer dog bites ✅

Dogs live freely, no cages ✅

Let’s protect our furry friends the smart and humane way! ❤️🐶

comment_text:
This policy is a shameful, backward step that reflects poorly on our values as a nation. Far more people in India die every year from potholes, unsafe infrastructure, and violent crimes such as rape—issues that should take priority if we truly care about human safety and dignity. Instead of making Delhi infamous again for cruelty, we should be working to shed the global stigma of being called the “rape capital of the world.”

If the goal is to control the street dog population, the humane and effective approach is simple: sterilise, vaccinate, tag, and return them to their territories; ban the breeding and sale of foreign dog breeds; and actively promote adoption of Indian dogs as a moral responsibility for all citizens. A country’s humanity is reflected in how it treats its animals—right now, this policy is sending the wrong message to the world.

Respected Sir/Madam

I place on record my grave charge that Dr. S.K. Yadav, Deputy Director (Veterinary Services), Municipal Corporation of Delhi, In-Charge Rabies Control Programme, is corrupt and compromised, and that his continuing presence in office has subverted Delhi’s Animal Birth Control (ABC) Programme, endangered public health, and precipitated judicial intervention against the city.

I. Not a policy failure but an officer‑led collapse
Scientific and policy consensus is unequivocal: removal/confinement of dogs does not reduce dog density or control rabies; only sustained mass dog vaccination and sterilisation are effective. This is the World Health Organization’s position and regional practice guidance.

Global rabies‑control literature shows mass dog vaccination is the proven tool; culling/warehousing undermines herd immunity and worsens outcomes.

Despite this, Delhi’s programme has been allowed to rot administratively and ethically, creating the very conditions that led to the Hon’ble Supreme Court’s order dated 11.08.2025 in Suo Motu W.P.(C) No. 5 of 2025 directing removal and confinement of street dogs—an outcome traceable to non‑implementation, data fraud, and oversight failure under the current MCD leadership.

II. Documented misconduct and pattern of fraud linked to Dr. S.K. Yadav
A. Prior judicial findings of bogus allotments (tainted record):

The Hon’ble Delhi High Court (31.05.2007), in Common Cause v. Union of India, recorded that 67% of allotments in the Ghogha Dairy project made under the charge of Dr. S.K. Yadav were bogus, reflecting systemic fraud and maladministration within MCD. This is not mere allegation; it is on the judicial record.

B. Economic Offences Wing (EOW) criminal case:

The Indian Express (19.03.2012) reported that the EOW registered a case against Dr. S.K. Yadav over irregularities in awarding dairy plots in the Ghogha Dairy Colony, pursuant to CVC directions. This underscores a history of corruption investigation tied directly to this officer.

C. Ongoing legal non‑compliance in ABC execution:

The Delhi High Court (Oct 2023) has upheld/affirmed the ABC Rules, 2023 framework and its logic of regulated, recognised implementers (AWBI‑recognised agencies only). Yet, in Delhi, unrecognised agencies continue to be engaged and statutory oversight (Rule 9 monitoring committees, CCTV, monthly reviews) has been suppressed or rendered perfunctory—constituting wilful disobedience of binding law and court‑endorsed norms.

D. Fabrication of records/pecuniary motive (current programme failures):

RTI‑based mismatches between claimed sterilisation numbers and on‑ground population, and between claimed surgeries and non‑proportional procurement of vaccines/anaesthetics, indicate prima facie fabrication and fraudulent disbursement of public funds—a pattern entirely consistent with the officer’s documented past. (Details enclosed from RTI replies and field audits; annexed for inquiry.)

III. Offences involved
On the face of the above, the conduct under Dr. Yadav’s charge attracts, at minimum, inquiry under:

IPC provisions on cheating, criminal breach of trust, forgery and falsification of accounts, read with the Prevention of Corruption Act, 1988 (as amended);

Contempt jurisdiction for wilful disobedience of court‑endorsed ABC regime and continuing violation of statutory mandates (e.g., use of non‑recognised agencies contrary to ABC Rules, 2023, suppression of Rule‑mandated monitoring);

Municipal and service‑conduct rules on abuse of office and bringing the Corporation into disrepute.

I hereby request -

Forthwith suspension of Dr. S.K. Yadav pending probe, to prevent further tampering with records and intimidation of witnesses.

Time‑bound Vigilance & EOW inquiry into financial, administrative and legal violations in Delhi’s ABC/Rabies Control Programme, with forensic audit of procurement and billed surgeries (2016–2025), including cross‑verification of OT logs, drug ledgers, indents, and release registers.

Cessation of work by all non‑recognised agencies and re‑tender limited to AWBI‑recognised entities, in conformity with the ABC Rules, 2023 and the Delhi High Court’s pronouncements.

Reconstitution of the statutory Monitoring Committee under Rule 9 with monthly minuted meetings, real‑time CCTV at all ABC centres, and public dashboards for surgeries, ARV coverage, complications, and returns to location.

Public‑health pivot: a city‑wide Mass Dog Vaccination (MDV) schedule to rapidly restore herd immunity, aligned with WHO and One‑Health guidance. 

Failure to act will compel us to (a) move appropriate forums for contempt and criminal investigation, (b) seek court‑monitored implementation of ABC Rules, 2023 with third‑party audits, and (c) petition for personal cost and accountability for officers enabling persistent illegality.

I urge decisive action to restore legality, protect public health, and end the reign of impunity that has crippled Delhi’s ABC programme.

PETITION UNDER ARTICLE 32 OF THE CONSTITUTION OF INDIA


SEEKING ENFORCEMENT OF ARTICLE 21 AND ARTICLE 51A(g)

IN LIGHT OF WIDESPREAD VIOLATIONS OF THE PREVENTION OF CRUELTY TO ANIMALS ACT, 1960, AND SUPREME COURT DIRECTIONS IN AWBI v. A. NAGARAJA & ORS.



---


TO


THE HON’BLE CHIEF JUSTICE OF INDIA

AND HIS COMPANION JUSTICES

OF THE HON’BLE SUPREME COURT OF INDIA



1. FACTS LEADING TO THIS PETITION


1.1 The Petitioner is an animal activist and community feeder, actively involved in protecting and rehabilitating stray/community animals.


1.2 The present petition arises out of grave instances of cruelty to community dogs in multiple States, including Uttar Pradesh and Tamil Nadu, involving acts of poisoning, beating, deliberate vehicular assault, and stabbing/slitting — all in blatant violation of statutory provisions and binding Supreme Court orders.


1.3 The Hon’ble Supreme Court in Animal Welfare Board of India v. A. Nagaraja & Ors. (2014) and subsequent orders in 2015–2016 has categorically held that:

(a) No relocation or killing of community dogs is permissible except under extreme medical necessity.

(b) The right to life under Article 21 extends to all living beings.

(c) All authorities must ensure safety, feeding, and vaccination of stray animals.


1.4 Despite this, local authorities, police, and municipal bodies are either complicit or inactive, emboldening offenders and escalating violence against animals. Such brutality poses a direct risk to public safety — perpetrators of animal cruelty often escalate to violent crimes against humans.



---


2. VIOLATIONS OF LAW


2.1 Constitution of India


Article 21 – Right to life and personal liberty (extended to animals by SC).


Article 51A(g) – Fundamental duty to protect and improve natural environment and have compassion for living creatures.



2.2 Indian Penal Code, 1860


Section 428 – Mischief by killing/maiming an animal worth ₹10 or more.


Section 429 – Mischief by killing/maiming an animal worth ₹50 or more.


Section 506 – Criminal intimidation (where activists are threatened).



2.3 Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act, 1960


Section 11 – Prohibition of cruel acts including beating, kicking, overloading, or mutilating.


Section 12 – Penalty for practicing phooka or injurious operations.



2.4 Supreme Court Orders


AWBI v. A. Nagaraja & Ors., (2014) 7 SCC 547 – Recognition of animal rights under Article 21.


SC Interim Order dated 18.11.2015 & Final Order dated 09.03.2016 in AWBI v. People for Elimination of Stray Troubles (PEST) – Prohibition on relocation and killing of community dogs.

---


3. GROUNDS


A. Because the right to life under Article 21 extends to all living creatures and the continuing violence against community dogs violates this constitutional guarantee.


B. Because the State’s inaction amounts to breach of its duty under Article 51A(g) and statutory duties under the PCA Act.


C. Because the Hon’ble Supreme Court’s binding orders are being openly flouted.


D. Because unchecked violence against animals is a public safety hazard and criminological studies show a direct link between animal cruelty and violent crimes against humans.


---


4. PRAYERS


In light of the above, the Petitioner respectfully prays that this Hon’ble Court may be pleased to:


(a) Issue directions to all State Governments and Union Territories to strictly implement Sections 428–429 IPC, Sections 11–12 PCA Act, and the Supreme Court orders in AWBI v. A. Nagaraja & Ors..


(b) Direct immediate investigation and prosecution of all recent incidents of animal cruelty as per FIRs and photographic evidence annexed herein.


(c) Direct the issuance of a nationwide SOP for police and municipal authorities for handling community dogs in compliance with the PCA Act and SC orders.


(d) Constitute a State-level Animal Protection Task Force with power to act on cruelty complaints within 24 hours.


(e) Pass any other order as this Hon’ble Court may deem fit in the interest of justice


Instead of protecting their rights as recognised under Article 21 and Article 51A(g), any judicial or administrative action that permits or encourages killing, brutalisation, or mass culling of animals will embolden cruelty, desensitise society, and inevitably lead to greater violence towards humans themselves.


This Hon’ble Court has, in multiple precedents including AWBI v. Nagaraja (2014) and subsequent orders in 2016, affirmed that compassion towards animals is part of the constitutional fabric of India. Any contrary approach reverses years of progress and normalises inhuman conduct. Such permissive attitudes towards cruelty are contrary to the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act, 1960, the Indian Penal Code Sections 428–429, and the fundamental duty of every citizen to protect living creatures.


It is deeply disturbing that serious crimes such as rape, murder, and theft often require years or decades for justice, yet when a voiceless animal attempts to defend itself in the rarest of situations, such acts are magnified and punished with unprecedented swiftness. These creatures cannot speak, cannot plead for their lives, and exist entirely at the mercy of human beings. When humans turn into their tormentors, the animals’ suffering is silent yet extreme.


Trust justice prevails in India .

video_title: Supreme Court Directs Delhi Government to Tackle Stray Dog Menace with Urgent Policy Reforms
comment_text:
I honestly don’t understand why, in a country where crime rates are so high, people don’t stand up against criminal politicians and powerful wrongdoers—but removing innocent stray dogs suddenly becomes a top “priority” for national safety? Are you serious?

Yes, I won’t deny that stray dogs can sometimes cause problems. But they are far better than some humans—an animal will not attack unless it feels threatened, has had a traumatic past, or in rare cases acts unpredictably. If an attack has happened without reason, it’s likely an exception, not the rule.There are humane measures to address the stray population—sterilization programs, proper shelter homes, community care. But killing them? That’s the only solution people can think of? I cannot comprehend how cruel we have become.

So, your own safety matters so much that even the idea of a possible attack is enough for you to justify killing millions of innocent dogs? That is utterly shameful. If you cannot give life to someone, you have no right to take it away. And don’t think you’re free from guilt—if you support such killings, even without doing it yourself, you share in the sin.

video_title: Supreme Court Directs Delhi Government to Tackle Stray Dog Menace with Urgent Policy Reforms
comment_text:
Recently, we lost one of our relatives due to a dog bite incident. He was only 38 years old and has left behind two small daughters — one just 8 months old, and the other 4 years.

This is not just “one incident.” It’s a tragic reminder of what can happen when real concerns around stray dog aggression are ignored or downplayed.

As members of society, we cannot remain silent or hesitant anymore. Public safety must come first. 

It’s important that we condemn such situations firmly and demand real solutions, including controlling stray dog population growth — not by promoting cruelty, but through mass sterilization, responsible feeding, and clear accountability.

Let’s not allow love for animals to come at the cost of human lives. Humans and animals both deserve dignity — but not at the cost of one another. It’s time to work towards a balanced, practical solution — not just emotional arguments.

Appreciate the Supreme Court’s judgment directing Delhi-NCR civic bodies to capture and shelter stray dogs, ensuring public safety, preventing rabies, and protecting children, women, and elderly from growing stray dog threats.

video_title: Humane or Dangerous: Why Delhi’s Stray Dogs Could Vanish in Just 8 Weeks | Vantage with Palki Sharma
comment_text:
Dog Bite Cases: According to information provided by the government in the Lok Sabha, there were over 3.7 million (3,717,336) reported dog bite cases in India in 2024. Other reports cite a similar figure of around 2.2 million cases. This highlights a significant public health issue.



Rabies Deaths: The government has reported 54 "suspected human rabies deaths" in 2024. However, it's important to note that these figures are widely believed to be a significant underestimate. Many experts and organizations, including the World Health Organization (WHO), suggest that the actual number is much higher, with some studies estimating thousands of rabies deaths annually in India. The discrepancy is attributed to underreporting, lack of proper surveillance, and cases not being officially recorded, especially in rural areas.



These numbers underscore the serious public health challenge posed by the stray dog population in India and the need for comprehensive and effective measures to control their population and prevent the spread of rabies.

video_title: Humane or Dangerous: Why Delhi’s Stray Dogs Could Vanish in Just 8 Weeks | Vantage with Palki Sharma
comment_text:
These challenges are often complex, rooted in issues of public health, safety, and ecosystem balance.

1. Public Health and Safety Concerns

Rabies: This is arguably the most critical disadvantage. India accounts for a significant portion of global rabies deaths, and the vast majority of these cases are transmitted by dog bites. The lack of universal vaccination programs for the street dog population, particularly in rural areas, creates a constant risk. Children are particularly vulnerable to rabies due to their inability to recognize and avoid dangerous situations.


Dog Bites and Aggression: Reports of dog bites are widespread across India, with millions of cases reported annually. While not all bites are from stray dogs, their sheer numbers and territorial behavior, especially in packs, contribute significantly to the problem. These attacks can be unprovoked, particularly during mating seasons or when dogs are stressed or competing for food.


Other Zoonotic Diseases: Street dogs can carry and transmit other diseases to humans, such as leptospirosis and salmonellosis. Their presence in public spaces, and scavenging in open garbage, raises public health concerns.

Road Accidents: The presence of dogs on roads, particularly at night, can lead to traffic accidents, posing a risk to both drivers and the animals themselves.

2. Environmental and Ecological Impact

Threat to Wildlife: Street dogs are a major threat to native wildlife, especially in and around protected areas and national parks. They can prey on endangered species like the Great Indian Bustard, blackbuck, and Olive Ridley sea turtle eggs. They also compete with native predators, such as wolves and dholes, for food and territory.


Disease Transmission to Wildlife: Street dogs can transmit diseases like canine distemper to vulnerable wild animal populations, as has been observed in Asiatic lions in Gir National Park.

Interbreeding with Wild Canids: There is evidence of hybridization between stray dogs and wild canids like golden jackals, which can dilute the gene pool and unique adaptive traits of the wild species.

3. Social and Societal Challenges

Human-Animal Conflict: The issue of street dogs often creates friction between residents and animal welfare advocates. Disputes over dog feeding, aggressive behavior, and a general fear of dogs can lead to social tensions and even acts of cruelty against the animals.


Strain on Resources: Managing the stray dog population places a significant burden on local municipalities and animal welfare organizations. The costs and logistics of implementing effective sterilization (Animal Birth Control) and vaccination programs are a major challenge, often hampered by funding shortages and public apathy.


Welfare of the Dogs: The lives of street dogs are often brutal and short. They face malnutrition, injuries from vehicles, and disease. They are also subjected to cruelty from humans. The high turnover rate of the population, with many puppies dying within their first year, highlights the difficult conditions they endure.

*UP Stray dogs kill 3-year-old girl, 200 bite marks found* 

Kanwardeep Singh.

Bareilly: A three-year-old girl was mauled to death by a pack of feral dogs at Bandia village in CB Ganj area of Bareilly on Tuesday. According to doctors, there were at least 200 dog bite marks on her body.

Pari, daughter of Avdhesh Gangwar, a labourer, was the youngest of four sisters and a brother. On Tuesday evening, she was playing in the courtyard of their house while her elder sister Sunita was preparing dinner. Pari soon walked towards a field to play when around seven-eight hungry dogs pounced on her. According to locals, a youth heard her crying for help and rushed to rescue her. He too was bitten by the dogs when he snatched Pari from their clutches. She was rushed to hospital, where doctors declared her dead.

Pari's uncle Jitendra Ku-mar said, "She walked far from the house and no one in the family could hear her screams for help. The dogs even dragged her for nearly 50 metres and bit her all over the body, causing deep injuries, especially on the neck."CB Ganj SHO Ashok Kumar said, "We have sent a team to the village to verify the incident. The family refused to give the body for autopsy and buried it as per Hindu rituals. The municipal corporation has been informed about the incident and has been directed to take necessary steps to tackle the stray dog menace."

Jogendra Kumar, a local, told TOI, " *A few illegal slaughter houses were operating in the area and stray dogs used to feed on abattoir waste. But now such units have been closed, and these stray dogs have turned violent as they go hungry.* Locals are not in any position to feed these animals every day. People have written to the civic body many times regarding the stray dog menace, but their campaign usually ends after catching a few dogs. There have been 15 dog bite cases in the village in the recent past."

Source: The Times of India 
March -2- 2023

video_title: Supreme Court On Stray Dogs: SC Reserves Its Judgement On Relocation Of Stray Dogs In Delhi | N18V
comment_text:
Both dog lovers and haters want the same thing → fewer dogs on the streets & fewer rabies/bite cases.

1️⃣ Impossible task – Crores of dogs can’t just be caught or killed. Even years of effort won’t succeed.
2️⃣ Vacuum effect – Remove dogs → new unvaccinated, often more aggressive ones take their place → more bites, more rabies.
3️⃣ Global failures – China, Sri Lanka, Romania all tried culling. Backfired & Rabies increased.
4️⃣ Budget drain – Catching & sheltering lakhs of dogs = thousands of crores + massive space India doesn’t have. We have many other issues where this budget can be utilized.
5️⃣ Proven solution ignored – Sterilization + vaccination (ABC) works. It’s cost-effective, WHO-recommended, Indian law mandated. Govt has failed to scale it up.

👉 The truth: Only ABC reduces dogs on streets & protects people.

Before you come at me, I vaccinate and sterilize dogs every month from my own money. I adopted two rescues( indies) and most people like me who are fighting for strays are against breeds and breeding. 
Please don’t spread hate without knowing the full picture.

comment_text:
Supreme Court judge has passed a judgement against the law of the land! 
The Supreme Court has started behaving as if it is above the law and a law unto itself. 
Our laws forbid transfer of stray dogs from one place to another.

Where even humans are lacking basic of the basic, how can we house and feed millions of stray dogs who are territorial in nature and bound to attack each other?
The only way forward is for the government through municipalities to work with NGOs and volunteers to spay, neuter and tag stray dogs. 
Only the sick, crippled, old dogs and dogs with puppies need to be homed in animal shelters with proper veterinarian care.
This will cost far lesser than housing all stray dogs in shelters. 
This problem wouldn't arise if the municipalities did their job.
The government has to work with the NGOs and volunteers involved in stray animals welfare.

video_title: 'Stray Dogs Menace Needs Compassionate Solutions'; Watch Locals Take On Supreme Court Order
comment_text:
People keep calling themselves “animal lovers” when in reality, they’re just dog lovers. If they truly loved animals, they’d care for chickens, goats, fish, and even the so-called “ugly” creatures like cockroaches or snakes. But no, they happily eat mutton, chicken, and fish, while posting selfies with their imported breed dog. This isn’t love for animals, it’s selective affection for pets that make them feel good.

Street dogs are a serious public safety issue. Why should human children be taught to walk carefully, avoid eye contact, or carry sticks in their own streets? Streets are built for humans, not for territorial packs of animals. In nature, if an outsider enters a lion’s or dog’s territory, it’s attacked. Yet we’re told to “just be kind” while kids risk rabies, a disease that kills over 20,000 people in India every year.

And to those saying, “How can the government accommodate so many dogs?” — you are the reason this problem is out of control. You’re the ones stopping the municipality from catching dogs for years. You’re the ones feeding them on the streets, helping their numbers grow. You protect them from removal but then blame the government when the population explodes.

Also, stop confusing dog loyalty with “love for humans.” A dog is loyal to its pack, not to humanity. That’s just basic animal instinct. If you feed and protect it, you’re part of its pack. But to an unfamiliar child or passerby, the same “loyal” dog can turn aggressive because it sees them as an intruder in its territory. This is not betrayal — it’s exactly how wild animal packs behave. So no, a stray dog on the street is not automatically a friend just because it’s friendly to you.

Developed countries don’t allow free-roaming strays. They have shelters, strict breeding laws, and zero tolerance for animals attacking people. Here, activists feed strays in public, block municipal workers, and then act shocked when dog attacks rise. Feeding strays on the streets only increases their population and aggression. If you want to feed dogs, build a shelter and keep them there. Don’t make the whole community responsible for your choice.

Dog lives matter, yes. But human lives matter more. Protecting people and controlling stray populations is not cruelty, it’s common sense. If you oppose removing dangerous strays, you should be ready to take legal and financial responsibility if they harm someone. Until then, stop being a keyboard warrior and start being accountable.

video_title: Street Dog Verdict: Supreme Court Verdict on Delhi Stray Dogs Tomorrow | Landmark Case | NewsX
comment_text:
​I am fundamentally opposed to the killing of any animal. However, the reality of living with domestic dogs, or encountering stray animals, presents unavoidable challenges.
​Even well-cared-for household dogs can pose a risk; if one is not sufficiently vigilant, bites can occur. This is compounded by the fact that all dog breeds possess a naturally aggressive potential, regardless of which type you choose.
​My primary concern is for human well-being. While I acknowledge that humans are often flawed, in the debate between animal welfare and human safety, I believe we must address the issue of stray animals in our communities. Animals that are genuinely harmless and move freely are typically ignored, but those that pose a threat cannot be.
​Having spent time observing both dedicated pet owners and interactions with stray dogs, my conclusion remains firm: an animal, at the end of the day, is still an animal—and must be viewed through that lens of unpredictable instinct.

video_title: Delhi's Dog Debate: Public Health Crisis Or Ecological Disaster After SC Order? | India Today Debate
comment_text:
What India Can do regarding street furkids:
Goal
Reduce street-dog population and rabies incidence, improve public safety and dog welfare, by implementing a humane, scalable program combining mass sterilisation & vaccination, waste management, law & enforcement, and community engagement — measurable progress within 5 years and robust control in 10–15 years.
Phase 0 — Immediate / Quick wins (0–12 months)
Purpose: stop new deterioration, build capacity, communicate. Actions:
National task force (central + state veterinary/public health + NGOs) set up to coordinate policy and funding.
Mass public awareness campaign on: don’t abandon pets, responsible feeding, rabies prevention, report dog-bite cases.
Emergency rabies response: ensure PEP (post-exposure prophylaxis) availability at district hospitals; fast-track training for health workers on bite management.
Pilot high-impact ABC (Animal Birth Control) zones in 10–20 cities with highest bite/rabies incidence to demonstrate model & collect data.
Garbage cleanup blitzes in pilot zones to show rapid results when food sources are removed.
KPIs (12 months): task force formed; pilots launched; PEP stockouts eliminated in pilot districts; public campaign reach metric (e.g., x million impressions).
Phase 1 — Scale sterilisation + vaccination (1–4 years)
Purpose: reduce birth rates and rabies reservoir; show measurable decline in bite/rabies. Actions:
Scale up ABC program: mobile sterilisation teams, fixed clinics, night-surgery schedules, trained para-vets. Prioritise high-density urban wards and hotspots identified in pilots.
Capture–Sterilize–Vaccinate–Release (CSVR) standard operating procedure (SOP) across states — release only after recovery.
Data system: unique ID tagging (collar + photo + GIS location) and central database to track sterilised/vaccinated dogs and coverage rates.
Finance model: central matching grants to states + municipal budgets + NGO partnerships + CSR funding to cover surgeries, vaccines, meds, logistics.
Training & certification: accredit surgeons/teams, quality standards, animal welfare auditing.
Community dog-feeding zones: designate controlled feeding spots (away from traffic/markets) while sterilisation occurs.
KPIs (by year 4): 70%+ vaccination coverage in target zones; sterilisation rate high enough to reduce effective reproductive rate (target varies, but aim for sterilising majority of fertile females in hotspots); measurable drop in dog-bite incidence in pilot zones.
Phase 2 — Waste & habitat control + policy reforms (3–8 years)
Purpose: remove food sources & institutionalize prevention. Actions:
Modern municipal solid-waste management: sealed bins, covered transfer points, daily collection in dense urban wards; ban open garbage dumping near residential/market areas.
Regulation: mandatory pet registration + microchipping, mandatory sterilisation for adopted/rescued animals (incentives/subsidies).
Strict anti-abandonment enforcement: fines + prosecution for deliberate abandonment.
Expand shelters & adoption networks: municipally funded temporary holding centers, NGO-run adoption drives, foster networks.
Integrate into urban planning: dog-proofing waste bins, market sanitation, community feeding infrastructure.
Education: school curriculum modules on animal welfare, rabies prevention and responsible pet ownership.
KPIs (by year 8): marked reduction in accessible food in urban hotspots; established registration coverage in major cities; sustained low rabies incidence; improved adoption rates from shelters.

video_title: Supreme Court Orders Removal of Stray Dogs from Delhi Streets | Delhi NCR | Stray Dogs of India
comment_text:
1. I live in a society in Mumbai that houses several dogs of which few are notoriously menacing. They have attacked most people unprovoked. Having had several pets ourselves, we understand canine behaviour well. These few strays are wild and dangerous. People in the society are scared to go into parking lots and certain areas or even walk in the garden without sticks. These dogs attacked me twice unprovoked. But the animal lovers in the society won't let the BMC take even the few ferocious dogs out of the many strays in our complex. They file FIRs and call people in high places just to avoid getting these dogs taken away. It's a huge problem. True, of the 2 dozen adult dogs+their litter, only a handful are rogue. But the dog lovers won't allow even the menacing ones who have bitten and attacked most of the society members to be taken away. Neither are they willing to adopt them and take them home! All they did is get them vaccinated eons ago and feed them daily. So what about human safety? Everyone is scared of the rotten mangoes. And as much as we have no problem with the remainder of the dogs, we cannot do anything about the menacing ones because of the unable-to-reason dog lovers!

2. If you are concerned about the conditions of the captured dogs, please adopt them or build community shelters or donate something small towards these shelters or even volunteer there regularly.

3. My brother was attacked bitten by a stray dog some years ago at another location in Mumbai. He had to undergo the treatment which deterred his travel plans for work.

4. Yes, we should respect life in all forms. The sanctity of life should be extended to mosquitoes, rats, yeast, and pathogens too. But when it comes down to a choice, when it comes to safety, we need to choose logically.

5. And yes, my mother in law died of lung fibrosis. I watched her suffer with oxygen cylinders attached to her as she gasped for every breath in agonizing pain. So, please forgive me if I choose my own species, my own family over strays and pigeons!

video_title: Stray Dog Attack | 8-Week Deadline For Dog-Free Delhi: Big Top Court Order On Stray Dog Menace
comment_text:
🚨 1 Million Dogs in Shelters? Let’s Do the Math 🚨

Delhi has ~10 lakh stray dogs. Court says: put them ALL in shelters.

Even at the cheapest possible rates:
🍲 Food: ₹20/day × 10,00,000 dogs = ₹2 crore/day → ₹7,300 crore/year
💉 Basic care: ₹100/month × 10,00,000 = ₹1.2k crore/year
👷 Staff: 1 person for 20 dogs → 50,000 staff × ₹20k/month = ₹1,000 crore/year (₹12k crore/year)
🏞 Land: 25 sq ft/dog → 574 acres needed

💰 TOTAL running cost = ₹20,500 crore/year — without counting land cost, building cost, or catching/transporting the dogs.

If done humanely with proper space & care → ₹1.99 LAKH crore/year + nearly 7,000 acres + 2 lakh staff.

⚠️ Clearly, mass sheltering is financially & logistically impossible.
✅ Real solution: sterilisation, vaccination, community feeding, adoption.

video_title: SC Orders All Stray Dogs In Delhi NCR Rounded Up Amid Rising Bite Cases | India Today News
comment_text:
If dogs were absent from Delhi's ecosystem, several changes in the food chain would likely occur. A primary consequence would be a rise in the populations of animals that dogs typically prey on, such as rats and smaller rodents, which could lead to increased damage to crops and property. Additionally, the scavenging role dogs play in disposing of organic waste would be diminished, potentially impacting cleanliness and sanitation, and creating opportunities for other scavengers to fill that niche. 
Here's a more detailed breakdown:
1. Population Fluctuations in Prey Species:
Increased Rodent Populations:
Dogs are natural predators of rats and mice, which are common in urban environments like Delhi. Without this predation pressure, rodent populations would likely increase, potentially leading to greater agricultural damage and the spread of diseases.
Impact on Other Small Animals:
Dogs also prey on other small animals like rabbits and some bird species. Their absence could lead to population increases in these animals as well, impacting the balance of the local ecosystem. 
2. Changes in Scavenging and Waste Management:
Rise in Other Scavengers:
Dogs play a significant role in consuming organic waste in Delhi. If they were absent, other scavengers like crows, kites, and potentially larger animals like stray cattle might become more prominent in consuming this waste.
Potential for Sanitation Issues:
With a reduced scavenging force, organic waste might accumulate more in certain areas, potentially leading to sanitation problems and increased risk of disease transmission. 
3. Potential Impact on Human-Animal Interactions:
Changes in Disease Dynamics:
While dogs can be carriers of rabies, their absence could also affect the transmission dynamics of other diseases that they may carry or be affected by.
Shift in Human Perception:
The absence of dogs could lead to changes in how humans perceive and interact with their environment, potentially impacting the cultural significance of dogs in Indian society. 
4. Ecosystem Imbalance:
Disrupted Food Webs:
The removal of a top predator like a dog can have cascading effects throughout the food web, potentially impacting the populations of multiple species.
Altered Biodiversity:
Changes in predator-prey relationships and scavenging patterns can alter the overall biodiversity of the area. 
It's important to note that the exact changes would depend on various factors, including the specific environment, the types of other animals present, and human interventions.

video_title: SC Orders All Stray Dogs In Delhi NCR Rounded Up Amid Rising Bite Cases | India Today News
comment_text:
Respected Rahul ji,

I seek your kind attention to a matter that is causing serious distress to citizens across the country—the rapid increase in stray dog populations despite ongoing sterilization programs.

If sterilization drives have been conducted properly over the past several years, the number of stray dogs should logically be declining. However, the reality on the ground is quite the opposite: their numbers appear to be growing, and so are the incidents of dog bites, road accidents, and fatalities.

This raises serious questions about:

The actual coverage and execution of sterilization programs by municipal and local bodies.

Transparency and accountability in reporting sterilization figures.

Whether the Animal Birth Control (ABC) Rules in their current form are effective in ensuring public safety.

The recent Supreme Court judgment (August 11, 2025) on Delhi-NCR, directing removal of stray dogs from public spaces and relocation to shelters, sets a clear precedent. I humbly request you to take up this issue in Parliament and with relevant ministries so that such measures are implemented nationwide.

Public safety must be our first priority. Preventable tragedies should not be allowed to continue

Human life must always come first. The pain and loss suffered when a loved one dies—whether from a road accident caused by stray dogs or from a dog bite—is something one can truly understand only when it happens within their own family. Such tragedies leave behind irreparable grief.

I wholeheartedly appreciate and congratulate the Hon’ble Judges of the Supreme Court for their recent order addressing the stray dog menace. Their decision reflects deep concern for public safety and compassion grounded in practical reality. This order should not remain confined to one region; it must be implemented uniformly across all states in India without delay.

I also urge civic authorities to focus on keeping our roads clean—not only of litter, but also of the faeces and waste left by stray dogs—so that public spaces remain safe and hygienic for all citizens.

Swift and decisive action in line with the Supreme Court’s directions will save lives, prevent suffering, and restore public confidence in our civic systems.

video_title: SC's Controversial Order: Stray Dogs to be Removed from Delhi | NEXT IAS
comment_text:
If dogs were absent from Delhi's ecosystem, several changes in the food chain would likely occur. A primary consequence would be a rise in the populations of animals that dogs typically prey on, such as rats and smaller rodents, which could lead to increased damage to crops and property. Additionally, the scavenging role dogs play in disposing of organic waste would be diminished, potentially impacting cleanliness and sanitation, and creating opportunities for other scavengers to fill that niche. 
Here's a more detailed breakdown:
1. Population Fluctuations in Prey Species:
Increased Rodent Populations:
Dogs are natural predators of rats and mice, which are common in urban environments like Delhi. Without this predation pressure, rodent populations would likely increase, potentially leading to greater agricultural damage and the spread of diseases.
Impact on Other Small Animals:
Dogs also prey on other small animals like rabbits and some bird species. Their absence could lead to population increases in these animals as well, impacting the balance of the local ecosystem. 
2. Changes in Scavenging and Waste Management:
Rise in Other Scavengers:
Dogs play a significant role in consuming organic waste in Delhi. If they were absent, other scavengers like crows, kites, and potentially larger animals like stray cattle might become more prominent in consuming this waste.
Potential for Sanitation Issues:
With a reduced scavenging force, organic waste might accumulate more in certain areas, potentially leading to sanitation problems and increased risk of disease transmission. 
3. Potential Impact on Human-Animal Interactions:
Changes in Disease Dynamics:
While dogs can be carriers of rabies, their absence could also affect the transmission dynamics of other diseases that they may carry or be affected by.
Shift in Human Perception:
The absence of dogs could lead to changes in how humans perceive and interact with their environment, potentially impacting the cultural significance of dogs in Indian society. 
4. Ecosystem Imbalance:
Disrupted Food Webs:
The removal of a top predator like a dog can have cascading effects throughout the food web, potentially impacting the populations of multiple species.
Altered Biodiversity:
Changes in predator-prey relationships and scavenging patterns can alter the overall biodiversity of the area. 
It's important to note that the exact changes would depend on various factors, including the specific environment, the types of other animals present, and human interventions.

video_title: SC's Stray Dog Verdict: Pan-India Rules Ban Street Feeding, Aggressive Dogs To Be Sheltered
comment_text:
Eventhouh all the stray dogs are sterilised  and given Antirabic vaccinations, they will never lose their aggressive behaviour while they are in a large group and insearch of food.
They must not be allowed to live freely in public places. 
Another major fact is that giving one dose of Antirabic vaccines does not give life long immunity to these dogs. 
In case one of those ones or a group of them are bitten by a Rabid animal,  surely they will develop Rabies and bite other dogs , animals and large number of people. 

Unless the number of Stray dogs 🐕 in the streets are controlled,  we will never be free from the threat of dog bites and resultant Rabies. 
So none of the above suggestions are a permanent 💯 % effective measure for solving the very serious public health issue of INDIA 🇮🇳. 
Being a Veterinarian for the last 40 years and from the latest Scientific informations available,  these are the real facts. 
Ofcourse I do honour the Verdict of the Honorable Supreme Court of INDIA 🇮🇳.

And look what Delhi is doing now not so different

This policy is a shameful, backward step that reflects poorly on our values as a nation. Far more people in India die every year from potholes, unsafe infrastructure, and violent crimes such as rape—issues that should take priority if we truly care about human safety and dignity. Instead of making Delhi infamous again for cruelty, we should be working to shed the global stigma of being called the “rape capital of the world.”

If the goal is to control the street dog population, the humane and effective approach is simple: sterilise, vaccinate, tag, and return them to their territories; ban the breeding and sale of foreign dog breeds; and actively promote adoption of Indian dogs as a moral responsibility for all citizens. A country’s humanity is reflected in how it treats its animals—right now, this policy is sending the wrong message to the world.

video_title: SC Stray Dogs Order That Split India | Non-Brutal Solution To This Menace Possible? | Akash Banerjee
comment_text:
The current stray dog situation reflects a serious governance failure. Simply stopping people from feeding them is not a solution—when hungry, dogs become aggressive hunters, and hunger can drive unpredictable behavior.
We must remember that dogs are domesticated animals that recognize humans as leaders when kept within a household or compound. However, when they gather in open areas or forests, they instinctively form packs and select leaders, much like wolves. In such situations, their behavior can become dangerous.
The municipality can consider this option: take strict action by targeting one gender—either female or male dogs, whichever is fewer in ratio—and relocating them to shelters. Over the next 5 to 10 years, this approach could significantly reduce and control the stray dog population

video_title: Stray Dog News | India's Stray Policy Gone To Dogs? Let's Not Stray From The Solution
comment_text:
Stray Dogs & Cattle in the street of India are a real havoc and menace. We need to understand this a health concern with more than 37.17L dog bites recorded (last year) and over 10,000 dog bites every single day in India. Though, we all love animals, especially dogs as a pet, there is a difference between stray dogs and the ones we shelter at homes.
With over 20,000 Rabies deaths in India and over 20,000 vehicle accidents due to stray dogs, it is a real concern and needs to be addressed. As much as we are dog lovers, we need to be taking precautions for the safety of old parents, little children and especially walking and traveling in Two-wheelers. I’ve been chased by dogs without any provocation, and I have witnessed many ruthless dogs causing menace and fear among people while walking or running. If you are so much worried about street dogs, please feel free to shelter them in your houses. In India alone we have close 6 crore street dogs and I firmly believe there are more than 3-4 crore street dogs that are not vaccinated and show aggression such as barking, chasing, or biting. If you are so worried, STOP bursting crackers during Diwali and adopt those dogs while being sheltered. I’m very much in agreement with the SC decision and its high time; the concerned authority is also taken accountable for such a menace and huge spike in street dog population.
